III.\tab Background Subtraction\par 
\tab \tab two-dimensional detectors offer best prospects for accurate background subtraction\par 
\tab \tab single element detectors can work, with some effort; possible techniques include:\par 
\tab \tab 1.\tab chopping to a point the same distance from Saturn:  doesn't work, due to the complex brightness contours produced by the rings and diffraction bars\par 
\tab \tab 2.\tab measuring the background at several positions surrounding your object, such as to the north, south, east, and west:  doesn't work, because the average of these is not usually the same as the background at your object\par 
\tab \tab 3.\tab chopping to a point diametrically opposite the center of Saturn:  best bet for those who can't change aperture sizes easily, because there is some symmetry to the scattered light background, but very sensitive to positioning errors, especially when working closer to the planet, where the brightness gradient is steeper\par 
\tab \tab 4.\tab chopping between concentric apertures of different sizes:  known to work well for Triton and Deimos, but requires additional calibration observations;\par 
\par 
